  "author_association": "NONE",
  "body": "Docker 1.5 [introduced read-only containers](https://blog.docker.com/2015/02/docker-1-5-ipv6-support-read-only-containers-stats-named-dockerfiles-and-more/). I\u2019ll quote from their release notes:\n\n> By using this capability in combination with volumes, you can make sure containers only persist data where it can be managed in a known location.\n\nI\u2019d like to have kubernetes start all of my containers using `--read-only`, just so that I know there is no data which is stored in temporary storage and then lost when the container is restarted/rescheduled/\u2026\n\nBased on reading https://cloud.google.com/container-engine/docs/spec-schema, I don\u2019t think kubernetes supports a read-only flag for the entire container, only for storage volumes. Hence, I\u2019d like to suggest introducing a read-only flag for the entire container.\n\nWhat do you think?\n",
